   =20
      Cell phones
   =20
 =20

The rule, according to the US Securities and Exchange Commission, is that i=
f you work at an investment bank or a brokerage firm or an investment advis=
er, you are allowed to communicate with your colleagues and clients about b=
usiness on =E2=80=9Cofficial channels,=E2=80=9D and you are not allowed to =
communicate with them about business on =E2=80=9Cunofficial channels.=E2=80=
=9D There are some obvious cases:
=09You are allowed to use your firm=E2=80=99s email system, and Bloomberg m=
essaging, and other electronic communications channels that are approved an=
d monitored and archived by your firm.=09I guess you are allowed to put a l=
etter in the mail? If you type it in Word on your office computer? Can=E2=
=80=99t imagine it comes up that often.=C2=A0=09You are=C2=A0not allowed to=
 message your colleagues or clients about deals by WhatsApp or text message=
 on your personal cell phone.

The point of this, I suppose, is to make sure that all discussions of work =
are archived and searchable by your firm=E2=80=99s compliance department an=
d the regulators. It doesn=E2=80=99t really accomplish those goals. For ins=
tance, I think that these cases are also pretty obvious, though this is not=
 legal advice and I=E2=80=99m not 100% sure:
=09You can talk to your colleagues about work when you=E2=80=99re sitting a=
t your desk, or in a conference room, or at lunch, even though those conver=
sations will not be recorded and archived.=09You can have meetings with cli=
ents in conference rooms, or at restaurants, or on the golf course, even th=
ough those conversations will not be recorded and archived.

It=E2=80=99s not really the case that all business-related communications n=
eed to be in written electronic archived searchable form. It=E2=80=99s just=
 that they need to be=C2=A0either that=C2=A0or in person.
  [1]
=C2=A0There are two allowable levels of formality, (1) formal archived writ=
ten communication and (2) in-person communication. Either is fine, but ever=
ything=C2=A0in between=C2=A0is suspect.
There is something counterintuitive about this. You might=C2=A0feel=C2=A0th=
at texting your colleagues is=C2=A0like=C2=A0in-person communication, that =
it=E2=80=99s a substitute for informal face-to-face chatting, and that ther=
efore it=E2=80=99s okay, but the SEC disagrees. To the SEC, texting is a su=
bstitute for official email, and if you text on an unrecorded personal phon=
e you are getting around your firm=E2=80=99s recordkeeping requirements.
The=C2=A0SEC=E2=80=99s rules require brokerage firms to preserve =E2=80=9Co=
riginals of all communications received and copies of all communications se=
nt =E2=80=A6 (including inter-office memoranda and communications) relating=
 to its business as such.=E2=80=9D And the SEC has been methodically workin=
g through every big investment bank and brokerage, examining their records,=
 sampling some employees=E2=80=99 personal phones, discovering that every s=
ingle bank with no exceptions whatsoever has employees who talk about work =
on texts or WhatsApp, and fining those banks millions of dollars for record=
keeping failures.=C2=A0We have   talked=C2=A0a few   times about this enfor=
cement   push, and I have argued that the SEC has aggressively=C2=A0expande=
d=C2=A0the recordkeeping requirements.=C2=A0In the olden days, almost all c=
ommunication was informal and not recorded, and only formal decisions were =
memorialized in typed and carbon-papered memos, so the SEC had access only =
to a pretty limited slice of communications. Now, vastly more informal comm=
unication is text-based, and texting is a substitute for conversation, not =
for formal memos. I   once wrote:

The SEC might plausibly come to a broker in 1948 and say =E2=80=9Cshow me a=
ll of your internal communications for the last two years,=E2=80=9D and he =
(he) might hand the SEC, like, 30 memos, and the SEC might say =E2=80=9Cah =
right that=E2=80=99s a reasonable number of memos=E2=80=9D and then go read=
 them.
One thing that has happened in the intervening 74 years is that written com=
munication has become much much much much much much much easier and more ca=
sual. I used to work on a desk at Goldman Sachs Group Inc., where the defau=
lt method of communication with someone who sat two seats away from you was=
 instant messaging.=C2=A0There were some mornings when I sent more than 100=
 inter-office memoranda, though like 20 of them would be =E2=80=9Clol=E2=80=
=9D or =E2=80=9Cfml.=E2=80=9D

But you can certainly   see where the SEC is coming from. For one thing, ev=
ery single firm is uniformly guilty, so it is easy to extract large fines f=
rom all of them; the SEC is not exactly a profit-maximizing entity but it i=
s not entirely not that either. For another thing, this enforcement push is=
 very helpful for=C2=A0other=C2=A0enforcement pushes: The upshot of these c=
ases is not only that investment banks and brokers pay big fines now, but a=
lso that they will do a more conscientious job of discussing business only =
on monitored channels, so that when the=C2=A0next=C2=A0scandal happens the =
SEC will have an easier time gathering evidence.=C2=A0
You could think up weirder hypotheticals about what is and isn=E2=80=99t al=
lowed:
=09If you want to arrange a golf outing with a client, can you text her fro=
m your personal phone saying =E2=80=9Clet=E2=80=99s play golf tomorrow=E2=
=80=9D? On the one hand, that is not a communication about a deal. On the o=
ther hand, if you regularly discuss deals on the golf course, it=E2=80=99s =
kind of about a deal.=C2=A0=09Can you text a client restaurant recommendati=
ons, or memes, from your personal phone? Ask her how her family is doing? Y=
ou=E2=80=99re not discussing deals, but of course the entire client relatio=
nship is part of the process of=C2=A0getting=C2=A0deals; you are not chatti=
ng with her out of pure friendship. It=E2=80=99s kind of a business communi=
cation.=09If you meet with a client in a conference room, write a draft pla=
n for a deal on a legal pad, and then hand her the legal pad, is that a for=
mal written communication that should have been made on official channels? =
What if you write it on a whiteboard? What if you meet with her in a restau=
rant and write it on a napkin? Will the SEC fine your bank, saying =E2=80=
=9Ca managing director once communicated with a client about a deal on a na=
pkin, instead of on official channels=E2=80=9D? That would be a fun complai=
nt.=09Can you send clients=C2=A0LinkedIn=C2=A0messages about business? On t=
he one hand, I guess your firm doesn=E2=80=99t monitor and archive LinkedIn=
 messages. On the other hand, man, it is LinkedIn. There is no form of comm=
unication on earth that=C2=A0feels=C2=A0more formal and official than Linke=
dIn, or more earnest and businesslike. It just seems impossible to do crime=
s on LinkedIn.
  [2]



I don=E2=80=99t know, I pose these questions mostly rhetorically, but now w=
e have an answer to the last one. The  SEC, and the  US Commodities Futures=
 Commission, brought a batch of new enforcement actions today, against BNP =
Paribas, Soci=C3=A9t=C3=A9 G=C3=A9n=C3=A9rale, Wells Fargo, Moelis & Co., H=
oulihan Lokey, some others, it doesn=E2=80=99t matter, in the long run the =
list will be =E2=80=9Cevery investment bank and brokerage and investment ma=
nager.=E2=80=9D
  [3]
=C2=A0All of the firms settled, because what else are you gonna do.=C2=A0=
=C2=A0\ Bloomberg calculates that today=E2=80=99s penalties are $260 millio=
n for the CFTC and $289 million for the SEC, and that =E2=80=9Ctotal fines =
for the probes into messaging practices have now crossed $2.5 billion, maki=
ng it one of the biggest crackdowns on Wall Street of the last decade,=E2=
=80=9D despite nobody being harmed by this conduct.=C2=A0And there are so m=
any more targets to go! They haven=E2=80=99t even touched the   private equ=
ity firms yet! The   hedge funds! There will be SEC lawyers who have long l=
ucrative careers that consist exclusively of fining financial firms for usi=
ng WhatsApp.
Anyway though here=E2=80=99s a line from the SEC=E2=80=99s  SocGen case:
Similarly, a managing director who is head of a capital markets desk exchan=
ged text, WhatsApp, and LinkedIn messages with at least six other SGAS empl=
oyees.
There is no allegation that this managing director sent any nefarious Linke=
dIn messages; he was not sending his colleagues LinkedIn messages that were=
 like =E2=80=9Chey let=E2=80=99s spoof the price of this stock.=E2=80=9D I=
=E2=80=99m sure he was sending them LinkedIn messages like =E2=80=9CI would=
 like to endorse you for Capital Markets Structuring and Networking.=E2=80=
=9D But it turns out that even LinkedIn is too spicy for the SEC.

