   =20
      ESG
   =20
 =20

For a while, environmental, social and governance investing was a hot marke=
ting=C2=A0tool in the investing world: If you did ESG, some people would sa=
y =E2=80=9Coh ESG I like that,=E2=80=9D and nobody would say =E2=80=9Coh ES=
G I don=E2=80=99t like that,=E2=80=9D so you would gain customers and not l=
ose any. And because ESG was a fairly fuzzy concept, you could =E2=80=9Cdo =
ESG=E2=80=9D without too much effort: If you just bought the stocks that yo=
u wanted to buy, but before you clicked =E2=80=9Cbuy=E2=80=9D you spent=C2=
=A0five seconds asking yourself =E2=80=9Cdo I feel like this company is pre=
tty green,=E2=80=9D that was probably ESG enough to slap the label on your =
fund.
Not anymore! Now lots of people =E2=80=94=C2=A0primarily US Republican poli=
ticians=C2=A0=E2=80=94=C2=A0say =E2=80=9Coh ESG I hate that,=E2=80=9D so th=
e ESG label will alienate lots of customers. And lots of other people still=
 say =E2=80=9Coh ESG I like that,=E2=80=9D but their standards have gone up=
: Now, if you advertise that you are ESG, you have to take it seriously. No=
w, if you advertise that you are ESG but people do not trust your ESG evalu=
ations,=C2=A0you can get in trouble =E2=80=94=C2=A0with customers and possi=
bly   with regulators =E2=80=94=C2=A0for =E2=80=9Cgreenwashing.=E2=80=9D
There are, I suspect, a number of investment managers and other related pro=
fessionals who got pretty into ESG when the getting was good, and now wish =
they had never heard of it. The  Financial Times reports:

S&P Global has stopped handing out scores to corporate borrowers on ESG cri=
teria, at a time of rising questions about their utility and political atta=
cks on such metrics.
The debt rating agency has since 2021 published scores from one to five for=
 a company=E2=80=99s exposure to each element of environmental, social and =
governance risks.
Payments company Visa, for example, had received a two for =E2=80=9CE=E2=80=
=9D and =E2=80=9CS=E2=80=9D and a three for =E2=80=9CG=E2=80=9D. FirstEnerg=
y, an Ohio utility that has been charged with corruption, received a four s=
core for =E2=80=9CG=E2=80=9D, S&P=E2=80=99s second-lowest grade.
Late last week S&P reversed course, saying that only text, not numerical sc=
ores, would comprise analysis of a company=E2=80=99s ESG matters.
=E2=80=9CWe have determined that the dedicated analytical narrative paragra=
phs in our credit rating reports are most effective at providing detail and=
 transparency on ESG credit factors material to our rating analysis,=E2=80=
=9D the rating agency said.

Very reasonable. My favorite part of the story, though, is this guy:

Tom Lyon, a professor at University of Michigan=E2=80=99s business school w=
ho has studied ESG ratings, said S&P move was =E2=80=9Cjust the latest exam=
ple of a company crumpling in the face of these Republican attacks=E2=80=9D=
.
Their attacks have also overshadowed real concerns about ESG ratings sold b=
y S&P and other financial firms, Lyon said. =E2=80=9CThey are not that reli=
able and they disagree.=E2=80=9D

=E2=80=9CI think they stopped doing ESG ratings for Reason X, and I disappr=
ove; they should have stopped doing ESG ratings for Reason Y.=E2=80=9D Yes,=
 right, all the more reason to stop!

