   =20
      Goldman in Russia
   =20
 =20

I guess that if you are a global investment bank with a presence in Russia,=
 you have some assets in Russia, and you have some liabilities in Russia. Y=
ou own Russian stocks and bonds and what have you, on the one hand, and on =
the other hand you have some derivatives trades where you owe Russian clien=
ts money. When Russia invaded Ukraine, you quickly had to stop dealing with=
 Russia, for sanctions and reputational reasons. This meant, on the one han=
d, that you couldn=E2=80=99t really=C2=A0use=C2=A0your Russian assets: Perh=
aps you could quickly dump some of your Russian stocks and bonds, but priva=
te stakes and anything illiquid are kind of just out of reach, sitting in R=
ussia but unavailable to you. And on the other hand, you can=E2=80=99t real=
ly pay your Russian liabilities: Wiring money to a sanctioned Russian bank =
to settle a derivatives trade, for instance, is going to make your complian=
ce officer nervous.
Probably the assets and liabilities partially offset each other, though, an=
d an approximate solution is to abandon everything, tell your Russian credi=
tors =E2=80=9Clook we have some Russian assets we=E2=80=99re not using but =
we=C2=A0can=E2=80=99t give them to you,=E2=80=9D and let the Russians=C2=A0=
sort it out:

A Russian court has frozen about $36mn worth of Goldman Sachs=E2=80=99 asse=
ts in the country after state-owned bank Otkritie, which is under western s=
anctions, filed a lawsuit against the US bank.
Otkritie accused Goldman of refusing to fulfil Rbs615mn ($6.4mn) of debt ob=
ligations under derivatives agreements between the two banks. According to =
court documents published earlier this month, Goldman had pointed to the sa=
nctions imposed against the Russian bank by the US and other western countr=
ies for not being able to settle the debt.
Otkritie claimed that Goldman Sachs wanted to leave Russia, which would mak=
e debt collection impossible, and requested that the court temporarily seiz=
e the US bank=E2=80=99s assets until the case was resolved. Goldman on Mond=
ay declined to comment on the court=E2=80=99s decision.
The temporarily frozen assets include a 5 per cent stake worth $27mn, based=
 on the latest share price, in Russia=E2=80=99s largest children=E2=80=99s =
goods retailer Detsky Mir, which means =E2=80=9Cchildren=E2=80=99s world=E2=
=80=9D. Goldman was a bookrunner for the company=E2=80=99s listing in Mosco=
w in 2017.
The document showed that the court ordered the temporary seizure of smaller=
 stakes in other Russian companies owned by a Luxembourg-registered Goldman=
 Sachs III SICAV fund.
These assets include shares in leading Russian lenders Sberbank and VTB, wh=
ich now owns Otkritie, as well as Gazprom, Lukoil, Russia=E2=80=99s largest=
 airline Aeroflot =E2=80=94 all under sanctions from the west =E2=80=94 and=
 one of the country=E2=80=99s top retailers, Magnit.=C2=A0
The Goldman fund had written down the price of these assets to zero, accord=
ing to its 2022 annual report. However, based on the companies=E2=80=99 lat=
est share price, their market value exceeds $9.3mn.

Yeah I mean those assets were frozen before, too. So were those liabilities=
. There=E2=80=99s a trade to be done, as long as Goldman doesn=E2=80=99t do=
 it.

