<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The rule, according to the US Securities and E=
xchange Commission, is that if you work at an investment bank or a brokerag=
e firm or an investment adviser, you are allowed to communicate with your c=
olleagues and clients about business on =E2=80=9Cofficial channels,=E2=80=
=9D and you are not allowed to communicate with them about business on =E2=
=80=9Cunofficial channels.=E2=80=9D There are some obvious cases:</p>
<ul style=3D"list-style-type: disc; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;">=
=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">You are allowed to use your firm=E2=80=
=99s email system, and Bloomberg messaging, and other electronic communicat=
ions channels that are approved and monitored and archived by your firm.</l=
i>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">I guess you are allowed to put a let=
ter in the mail? If you type it in Word on your office computer? Can=E2=80=
=99t imagine it comes up that often.=C2=A0</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-botto=
m: 5px;">You are=C2=A0<em>not </em>allowed to message your colleagues or cl=
ients about deals by WhatsApp or text message on your personal cell phone.<=
/li>
</ul>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The point of this, I suppose, is to make sure =
that all discussions of work are archived and searchable by your firm=E2=80=
=99s compliance department and the regulators. It doesn=E2=80=99t really ac=
complish those goals. For instance, I think that these cases are also prett=
y obvious, though this is not legal advice and I=E2=80=99m not 100% sure:</=
p>
<ul style=3D"list-style-type: disc; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;">=
=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">You can <em>talk </em>to your colleagu=
es about work when you=E2=80=99re sitting at your desk, or in a conference =
room, or at lunch, even though those conversations will not be recorded and=
 archived.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">You can have meetings w=
ith clients in conference rooms, or at restaurants, or on the golf course, =
even though those conversations will not be recorded and archived.</li>
</ul>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">It=E2=80=99s not really the case that all busi=
ness-related communications need to be in written electronic archived searc=
hable form. It=E2=80=99s just that they need to be=C2=A0<em>either </em>tha=
t=C2=A0<em>or</em> in person.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-=
1" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom=
-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !impor=
tant; background-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[1]</span>
</a>=C2=A0There are two allowable levels of formality, (1) formal archived =
written communication and (2) in-person communication. Either is fine, but =
everything=C2=A0<em>in between=C2=A0</em>is suspect.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">There is something counterintuitive about this=
. You might=C2=A0<em>feel=C2=A0</em>that texting your colleagues is=C2=A0<e=
m>like=C2=A0</em>in-person communication, that it=E2=80=99s a substitute fo=
r informal face-to-face chatting, and that therefore it=E2=80=99s okay, but=
 the SEC disagrees. To the SEC, texting is a substitute for official email,=
 and if you text on an unrecorded personal phone you are getting around you=
r firm=E2=80=99s recordkeeping requirements.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The=C2=A0<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloomber=
gbusiness.com/click/32335917.262411/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cubGF3LmNvcm5lbGwuZWR1L2N=
